8. CLAIMS (FINAL DRAFT)

Claim 1: A robotic leg system for extraterrestrial locomotion in low‑gravity, low‑pressure environments, comprising:

· a polycentric joint mechanism defined by a planar four‑bar linkage having a moving instantaneous center of rotation (ICR);
· a biarticular tendon element coupling a posterior anchor point of said polycentric joint to an anterior aspect of a distal ankle joint;
· characterized in that said biarticular tendon is coupled to an active pretensioning motor configured to modulate tendon slack and energy storage capacity dynamically across the locomotion cycle.

Claim 2: The system of Claim 1, further comprising a Dust‑Exclusion Housing, wherein all revolute joints of the four‑bar linkage are implemented as Cross‑Axis Flexure Pivots (CAFP) and are encapsulated within a hermetically sealed, flexible bellows system to prevent ingress of electrostatic regolith.

Claim 3: The system of Claim 1, further comprising a Series‑Parallel Elastic Actuator (SPEA) network including:

· a motor;
· a parallel elastic element configured to counterbalance a gravitational load;
· a non‑discrete friction clutch selected from the group consisting of a wrapped‑spring clutch and a magnetorheological brake, said clutch configured to lock said parallel elastic element at any continuous angular position to accommodate irregular terrain geometry without mechanical hunting.

Claim 4: A Terrain‑Adaptive Foot for use in near‑vacuum environments, comprising:

· a deformable membrane containing a granular media;
· a Mechanical Compression Piston configured to exert an internal confining pressure on said granular media;
· wherein the transition from a fluid‑like state to a jammed‑solid state is achieved through volumetric reduction independent of external atmospheric pressure.

Claim 5: The system of Claim 4, wherein the mechanical compression piston is operably coupled to the biarticular tendon such that an increase in tendon tension during a stance phase produces a proportional increase in confining pressure on the granular media, thereby achieving passive‑adaptive jamming without a dedicated actuator.

Claim 6: The system of Claim 1, wherein a controller is configured to implement a Contact‑Probability Impedance Law, reducing joint stiffness $\mathbf{K}_p$ proportionally to a decrease in sensed Ground Reaction Force ($F_z$), thereby preventing high‑velocity rebound effects in gravitational fields less than $0.4g$.

Claim 7: The system of Claim 1, wherein the controller further includes a Gravity‑Scaling Feedforward (GSF) term proportional to $(g_m - \ddot{z}_{hip})$, where $g_m$ is the local gravitational acceleration and $\ddot{z}_{hip}$ is the vertical acceleration of the hip joint, to prevent unintended liftoff during dynamic maneuvers.

Claim 8: The system of Claim 1, further comprising a tension sensor in the biarticular tendon, wherein a spike in tendon tension triggers an increase in a damping gain $\mathbf{K}_d$ of a knee actuator prior to an inertial measurement unit detection of a disturbance, thereby reducing reaction latency.

